WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.116 --> 00:00:09.180
(Bell dings)

2
00:00:09.370 --> 00:00:11.789
It shouldn't be primarily about pro bono.

3
00:00:12.141 --> 00:00:15.459
Look. I'm at Alicia's door. I'll ask her.

4
00:00:15.460 --> 00:00:17.040
(Knocking)

5
00:00:20.088 --> 00:00:21.300
Alicia Florrick?

6
00:00:21.897 --> 00:00:23.959
This is 603. She's in 903.

7
00:00:24.107 --> 00:00:25.017
Three floors up.

8
00:00:25.047 --> 00:00:26.264
Oh.

9
00:00:26.941 --> 00:00:28.068
Sorry.

10
00:00:28.098 --> 00:00:29.608
<i>(Knocking)</i>

11
00:00:32.014 --> 00:00:33.479
DUI.

12
00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:36.766
Wrong floor. Up. Three flights.

13
00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:38.698
<i>(Knocking)</i>

14
00:00:39.625 --> 00:00:41.359
903. You want 903.

15
00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:44.872
This is 603. See? 603.

16
00:00:44.902 --> 00:00:47.880
Six. That's three numbers less than nine.

17
00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:51.009
(Knocking)

18
00:00:51.145 --> 00:00:52.257
(Sighs)

19
00:00:54.050 --> 00:00:55.401
Oh. hello.

20
00:00:55.955 --> 00:00:57.790
Do you work for Mrs. Florrick?

21
00:00:58.516 --> 00:01:01.140
No. Although sometimes I feel like it.

22
00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:03.660
This is not her law firm. This is my home.

23
00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:06.059
See how pretty it is?
They rearranged the panel

24
00:01:06.089 --> 00:01:08.640
on the elevator so the six
is below the nine.

25
00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:11.960
Could you please tell your
client friends to learn to read?

26
00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:18.627
Are you here to see Alicia Florrick?

27
00:01:18.657 --> 00:01:19.699
Yep.

28
00:01:19.993 --> 00:01:22.206
A music case.

29
00:01:22.490 --> 00:01:24.236
Is this her door?

30
00:01:24.611 --> 00:01:25.970
Yep.

31
00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:29.194
(Knocking)

32
00:01:30.276 --> 00:01:32.279
Oh. good. It's you.

33
00:01:32.309 --> 00:01:34.770
Dear God. what is up
with that bitch downstairs?

34
00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:35.799
Rowby.

35
00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:37.790
Hey! I know. right?

36
00:01:38.284 --> 00:01:40.119
It's been centuries. huh?

37
00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:42.600
Look at you. working from home.

38
00:01:42.630 --> 00:01:44.540
You're like an artist now.

39
00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:45.595
You look great.

40
00:01:45.625 --> 00:01:47.290
I totally agree.

41
00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:50.080
I guess that's what happens when
you start working for yourself.

42
00:01:50.353 --> 00:01:51.448
I got a kid now.

43
00:01:51.478 --> 00:01:53.671
- Little Josh.
- Congratulations.

44
00:01:53.701 --> 00:01:55.581
Thanks. And. uh...

45
00:01:56.652 --> 00:01:58.708
I could use some legal help.

46
00:01:58.738 --> 00:02:00.494
♪ ♪

47
00:02:03.026 --> 00:02:07.109
♪ Good morning. magic sunshine.
it's a brand-new day ♪

48
00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:10.063
♪ I see you peeking through
my curtains. come in and ♪

49
00:02:10.093 --> 00:02:13.020
♪ Stay. stay. go bananas... ♪

50
00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:14.650
Mmm. Good song. Rowby.

51
00:02:15.401 --> 00:02:17.179
Thanks. It's my kid's birthday par...

52
00:02:17.180 --> 00:02:18.799
Oh. that's him. Little Josh.

53
00:02:18.829 --> 00:02:21.419
He's a total clown.
He likes to imitate everyone.

54
00:02:22.427 --> 00:02:24.010
♪ But then again I might ♪

55
00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:28.119
♪ Wake up and start my day
with magic sunshine... ♪

56
00:02:28.861 --> 00:02:30.190
You're good. Rowby.

57
00:02:30.220 --> 00:02:31.361
I am good.

58
00:02:31.391 --> 00:02:32.750
So what's the problem?

59
00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:34.750
Oh. Um...

60
00:02:35.309 --> 00:02:38.199
I got this letter from G.F.C Records.

61
00:02:38.918 --> 00:02:39.974
That's your label?

62
00:02:40.004 --> 00:02:43.159
Yeah. Well. my former label. yeah.

63
00:02:43.333 --> 00:02:45.135
- They say the song's theirs?
- Yeah.

64
00:02:45.165 --> 00:02:47.202
That's the part I don't get. I wrote it.

65
00:02:47.232 --> 00:02:48.847
I mean. I wrote that song.

66
00:02:48.877 --> 00:02:50.470
Ever since the whole "Thicky Trick" thing.

67
00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:51.622
I keep track of stuff.

68
00:02:51.652 --> 00:02:53.030
Are you still under contract with them?

69
00:02:53.060 --> 00:02:55.550
No. I finished that contract.
like. last year.

70
00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:56.810
So I don't understand.

71
00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:58.394
Have you recorded this song?

72
00:02:58.424 --> 00:03:03.059
No. I just play it at kids' birthday
parties. but that video is online

73
00:03:03.089 --> 00:03:04.807
and it's gone viral.

74
00:03:04.837 --> 00:03:06.885
S-Small viral. but viral.

75
00:03:06.915 --> 00:03:08.113
(Doorbell rings)

76
00:03:08.143 --> 00:03:09.330
I'll be right back.

77
00:03:11.298 --> 00:03:14.292
- Mrs. Dosek.
- Mrs. Florrick. I don't mean to be rude.

78
00:03:14.322 --> 00:03:17.319
but this is a residential building.
and you're conducting business here.

79
00:03:17.349 --> 00:03:19.081
Yes. I'll put a sign up
in the elevator. Mrs. Dosek.

80
00:03:19.111 --> 00:03:20.962
Okay. that's not gonna make a difference.

81
00:03:20.992 --> 00:03:23.208
Here. Your daughter's report card.

82
00:03:23.238 --> 00:03:24.101
- It's open.
- Yes.

83
00:03:24.131 --> 00:03:26.944
I thought it was addressed to me.
She got two Bs and three Cs.

84
00:03:26.974 --> 00:03:29.310
CARY: Hey. It's weird.
I went to the wrong floor.

85
00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:31.000
I think it's the way they changed
the numbers in the elevator.

86
00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:34.402
I'll make it all good. Mrs. Dosek.
Thank you. Good-bye.

87
00:03:34.432 --> 00:03:36.249
- Cary?
- So. am I late?

88
00:03:36.419 --> 00:03:38.350
Um... For?

89
00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:39.990
For Rowby.

90
00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.185
His new song.

91
00:03:41.215 --> 00:03:43.250
- How did you know?
- He came by Lockhart/Agos.

92
00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:44.775
I suggested it might be more
up your alley.

93
00:03:44.805 --> 00:03:46.685
but he wanted both of us.

94
00:03:46.715 --> 00:03:48.640
Cary. it's a kids' song.

95
00:03:48.670 --> 00:03:50.959
Yeah. with over a million views
on YouTube

96
00:03:50.989 --> 00:03:53.007
and with other labels
wanting to buy it.

97
00:03:53.037 --> 00:03:54.648
Oh.

98
00:03:54.678 --> 00:03:55.943
BEA: <i>Sorry I'm late.</i>

99
00:03:55.973 --> 00:03:57.517
I just came from a nasty encounter.

100
00:03:57.547 --> 00:03:58.909
so I might have some wine.

101
00:03:58.939 --> 00:04:01.430
That sounds good. Uh. what encounter?

102
00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:03.499
Oh. just some woman yelled at me.

103
00:04:03.529 --> 00:04:05.264
So how's the job search going?

104
00:04:05.294 --> 00:04:07.844
It's good. actually. In fact.
I wanted to thank you

105
00:04:07.874 --> 00:04:08.976
for offering to advise.

106
00:04:09.006 --> 00:04:10.515
but I got a job.

107
00:04:10.545 --> 00:04:12.330
Really? Fantastic.

108
00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:13.736
- Where?
- Uh. oddly. at the firm

109
00:04:13.766 --> 00:04:16.049
I was complaining about. Lockhart/Agos/Lee.

110
00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:18.163
Huh. I just left there a month ago.

111
00:04:18.193 --> 00:04:19.459
- Why'd you leave?
- Oh.

112
00:04:19.489 --> 00:04:20.869
the next shiny thing.

113
00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:23.400
Alicia Florrick. Now I'm not sure.

114
00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:25.496
That's where
I just got yelled at.

115
00:04:26.830 --> 00:04:27.819
Really?

116
00:04:27.849 --> 00:04:29.191
- She said that?
- Yes.

117
00:04:29.221 --> 00:04:30.465
So she might come back?

118
00:04:30.495 --> 00:04:32.150
She didn't say that. She just said

119
00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:33.240
she wasn't thrilled to be going to

120
00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:34.939
a law firm in someone's apartment.

121
00:04:34.969 --> 00:04:36.540
You have to apologize.

122
00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:38.290
- For what?
- For arguing a pro-life position.

123
00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:39.785
I wasn't arguing a pro-life position.

124
00:04:39.815 --> 00:04:42.100
Diane. no one can understand
what you were doing.

125
00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:44.060
If saying "I'm sorry"
gets us back in the door

126
00:04:44.090 --> 00:04:46.040
of a $4-million-a-year client.
why wouldn't you?

127
00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:47.900
- Because I'm not sorry.
- Do you want me to step out?

128
00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:48.516
- No.
- Yes.

129
00:04:48.546 --> 00:04:49.617
Will she meet with us?

130
00:04:49.647 --> 00:04:52.253
I don't know. I was speaking highly of you.

131
00:04:52.283 --> 00:04:54.019
How diverse you are here.

132
00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:55.600
We should bring the cripple
to the next meeting.

133
00:04:55.630 --> 00:04:56.929
- Oh. my God.
- What?

134
00:04:56.959 --> 00:04:57.801
The lawyer in the wheelchair.

135
00:04:57.831 --> 00:04:59.470
I know what you're saying.

136
00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:00.900
Will you call her?

137
00:05:01.359 --> 00:05:03.540
It's not really my account.

138
00:05:04.112 --> 00:05:06.988
Get her back in the door. and we'll talk.

139
00:05:11.123 --> 00:05:13.910
Well. look who's here to survey the spoils.

140
00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:15.210
Just seeing how you're doing.

141
00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:16.619
Our polling was off.

142
00:05:16.903 --> 00:05:17.659
I know.

143
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:18.874
Way off.

144
00:05:19.661 --> 00:05:20.900
Was that you. too?

145
00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:21.809
No.

146
00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:22.933
I really thought we were gonna

147
00:05:22.963 --> 00:05:25.119
- go on to New Hampshire.
- I know.

148
00:05:25.149 --> 00:05:26.409
Peter did. too.

149
00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:28.130
- But you didn't?
- You had me tempted.

150
00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.410
Your optimism was infectious.

151
00:05:31.858 --> 00:05:32.858
Well...

152
00:05:33.159 --> 00:05:34.345
You going on to Sanders?

153
00:05:34.375 --> 00:05:35.300
No.

154
00:05:35.330 --> 00:05:37.829
Congressional races. They're more fun.

155
00:05:38.092 --> 00:05:38.938
You staying?

156
00:05:38.968 --> 00:05:41.320
Yeah. Peter's got to get
back into governing.

157
00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:43.859
Well. I have some advice
for you. if you don't mind.

158
00:05:43.889 --> 00:05:46.117
- I'd never mind.
- Peter's in trouble.

159
00:05:46.521 --> 00:05:49.059
I don't know from where. I don't know who.

160
00:05:49.607 --> 00:05:52.672
But a governor who
returns home after a loss

161
00:05:52.702 --> 00:05:54.979
has a target on his back.

162
00:05:55.207 --> 00:05:57.334
Someone's gonna take a shot
at him.

163
00:05:57.364 --> 00:05:58.240
Who?

164
00:05:58.270 --> 00:05:59.730
I don't know.

165
00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:02.615
Watch out for friends.

166
00:06:03.635 --> 00:06:05.964
And on that sinister note.

167
00:06:05.994 --> 00:06:07.400
good-bye. Eli.

168
00:06:08.685 --> 00:06:10.099
Good-bye. Ruth.

169
00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:12.365
I wish...

170
00:06:14.257 --> 00:06:16.007
I had been better to you.

171
00:06:18.502 --> 00:06:20.252
I wish you had been. too.

172
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

173
00:06:44.404 --> 00:06:46.439
ROWBY: Who are you?

174
00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:49.019
Uh. Lucca Quinn. I work with Alicia.

175
00:06:49.806 --> 00:06:51.019
Doing what?

176
00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:52.989
Lawyering.

177
00:06:53.516 --> 00:06:54.611
Are you Rowby?

178
00:06:54.641 --> 00:06:55.641
Yeah.

179
00:06:56.416 --> 00:06:58.120
I have to tell you something.

180
00:07:00.321 --> 00:07:01.580
I think I love you.

181
00:07:01.610 --> 00:07:02.879
- (Laughs)
- No. I'm not kidding.

182
00:07:02.909 --> 00:07:05.127
Like. I'm serious. Like. I... it's crazy.

183
00:07:05.157 --> 00:07:07.100
Do you always decide things this fast?

184
00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:08.579
Uh... yeah.

185
00:07:09.319 --> 00:07:12.640
Hey. can... can I play some music for you?

186
00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:14.198
'Cause I think that's
the only chance I got.

187
00:07:14.228 --> 00:07:15.519
I don't think that's a good idea.

188
00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:17.224
We're about to start negotiations.

189
00:07:17.254 --> 00:07:18.229
Oh.

190
00:07:18.811 --> 00:07:20.330
You want to sit down?

191
00:07:20.906 --> 00:07:22.779
Oh! Yeah.

192
00:07:23.445 --> 00:07:25.550
Um... seriously. though. can I just say

193
00:07:25.580 --> 00:07:27.989
that. like. I... I never do this.

194
00:07:28.517 --> 00:07:32.759
But you... are the most
beautiful human being

195
00:07:32.789 --> 00:07:34.869
I have ever seen. like. in my life.

196
00:07:35.323 --> 00:07:37.392
- Thank you.
- It's crazy.

197
00:07:37.422 --> 00:07:38.902
I think we have company.

198
00:07:38.932 --> 00:07:40.579
Oh. hello.

199
00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:42.079
We're back facing each other.

200
00:07:42.109 --> 00:07:44.144
Andrea Stevens.

201
00:07:44.335 --> 00:07:46.677
And you have some
beautiful name. don't you?

202
00:07:46.707 --> 00:07:48.128
- Lucca Quinn.
- Lucca.

203
00:07:48.158 --> 00:07:49.539
(Laughing): Yes.

204
00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:51.455
And you've done something
different with your hair.

205
00:07:51.485 --> 00:07:52.579
- haven't you?
- No.

206
00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:55.280
Yes. Yes. in the front.
the bangs. I love it.

207
00:07:55.310 --> 00:07:56.769
Should I just give you guys some space?

208
00:07:56.770 --> 00:07:57.897
(Laughs)

209
00:07:57.927 --> 00:08:00.235
Rowby Canton. always fun
to hear from the artist.

210
00:08:00.265 --> 00:08:03.016
I'm just gonna set myself up
right over here. all right?

211
00:08:03.046 --> 00:08:04.333
Okay.

212
00:08:04.363 --> 00:08:05.719
Good morning. everyone.

213
00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.351
Um. I just want to say
that my client. Damon.

214
00:08:08.381 --> 00:08:10.441
has great respect for your talent. Rowby.

215
00:08:10.471 --> 00:08:11.559
Is that why he cut me loose?

216
00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:12.874
I cut you loose because...

217
00:08:12.904 --> 00:08:13.929
I don't think we need

218
00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:15.429
to go over the gory details.

219
00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.060
We respect you. Rowby.

220
00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:18.580
and that's why we sent you

221
00:08:18.610 --> 00:08:20.240
a cease and desist letter.

222
00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.179
Your YouTube video must come down.

223
00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:25.440
and we ask that you no longer
record the song

224
00:08:25.470 --> 00:08:27.030
"Good Morning Magic Sunshine"

225
00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:28.309
until you acquire our permission.

226
00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:32.462
Our client appreciates
all your respect. Andrea.

227
00:08:32.492 --> 00:08:35.439
um. but we respectfully reject
your cease and desist.

228
00:08:35.469 --> 00:08:37.934
Our client is the sole owner
of the song he composed.

229
00:08:37.964 --> 00:08:39.369
ANDREA: Unfortunately. that isn't true.

230
00:08:39.399 --> 00:08:41.979
As you can see from this contract.

231
00:08:42.009 --> 00:08:44.546
Rowby owes us another album.

232
00:08:44.576 --> 00:08:46.229
But I signed a two-album deal.

233
00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:47.821
and I gave you two albums.

234
00:08:47.851 --> 00:08:48.933
I rejected the second one.

235
00:08:48.963 --> 00:08:50.967
Damon. One sec.

236
00:08:51.509 --> 00:08:54.439
Mr. Stryk wants our artists to be happy.

237
00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:58.149
so he'll offer. uh... $1.500

238
00:08:58.150 --> 00:09:00.180
for Rowby to record a studio version.

239
00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:02.665
(Laughs): $1.500?

240
00:09:02.695 --> 00:09:03.598
- Seriously?
- Seriously.

241
00:09:03.628 --> 00:09:05.762
Oh. I would rather keep
playing birthday parties.

242
00:09:05.792 --> 00:09:07.672
ANDREA: And you know what?
You're very good.

243
00:09:07.702 --> 00:09:09.050
I have a daughter of my own.

244
00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:11.258
Adopted from China last year.

245
00:09:11.288 --> 00:09:12.540
And she loves it.

246
00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:14.609
But. again. it's our song.

247
00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.496
And we have to warn you. Rowby.

248
00:09:16.526 --> 00:09:19.530
that. um. we'll be pulling
your video off-line.

249
00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:21.569
No. you won't. You can't do that.

250
00:09:21.895 --> 00:09:22.980
Mm-hmm.

251
00:09:23.010 --> 00:09:25.003
- Yeah. actually. I just did.
- Can she do that?

252
00:09:25.033 --> 00:09:27.009
If we assert a copyright interest.

253
00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:28.720
we can unilaterally remove

254
00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:30.020
infringing videos.

255
00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:31.679
You can't assert a copyright...

256
00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.340
(All talking over each other)

257
00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:35.535
DIANE: Thank you. Bea.
for giving us a second chance.

258
00:09:35.565 --> 00:09:37.108
I don't know if that's what I'm doing.

259
00:09:37.138 --> 00:09:38.267
But I am here to listen.

260
00:09:38.297 --> 00:09:40.851
David Lee. I hope you remember me.
I'm a real fan of yours.

261
00:09:40.881 --> 00:09:42.325
I told Diane and David

262
00:09:42.355 --> 00:09:44.190
that you might be having some difficulty

263
00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:47.760
with the lack of infrastructure
at Florrick/Quinn.

264
00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:48.470
Yes.

265
00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:50.720
But I'm not sure if I'm ready
to come back here.

266
00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:52.289
Well. we would love to tell you...

267
00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:55.182
(Muffled arguing)

268
00:09:55.212 --> 00:09:57.379
- BEA: "How"?
- Yes. why don't you come

269
00:09:57.380 --> 00:09:58.676
- into Diane's office. and we can talk?
- Yes. good idea.

270
00:09:58.706 --> 00:10:00.103
BEA: I have a call to make first.

271
00:10:00.133 --> 00:10:02.250
DAVID: In the office!
Just... just right here.

272
00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:03.303
Happy with that.

273
00:10:03.333 --> 00:10:05.730
(All talking over each other)

274
00:10:08.246 --> 00:10:10.100
- What's wrong?
- What are they doing here?

275
00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:12.488
- G.F.C records?
- No. Alicia and her partner.

276
00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:13.649
I told you. We're on this case together.

277
00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:14.939
Are you trying to sabotage us?

278
00:10:14.969 --> 00:10:16.850
Not in our conference room. Cary.

279
00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:18.102
We have Bea Wilson here.

280
00:10:18.132 --> 00:10:20.283
- She's thinking of leaving them.
- I didn't know that.

281
00:10:20.313 --> 00:10:21.343
Well. get them out of here.

282
00:10:21.373 --> 00:10:24.402
ANDREA: All right. all right! Excuse me.

283
00:10:24.432 --> 00:10:27.240
Thank you for your attention.
everyone. Damon?

284
00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:29.359
Look. we really wanted
to settle this here.

285
00:10:29.389 --> 00:10:30.870
but you've given us no choice.

286
00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.930
- We are suing your client.
- For what?

287
00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:35.940
Breach of contract.
$3.1 million in damages.

288
00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:36.813
Three point what?

289
00:10:36.843 --> 00:10:38.769
Look at your contract. buddy.

290
00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:40.643
What part of my contract?

291
00:10:40.673 --> 00:10:41.576
It's their costs.

292
00:10:41.606 --> 00:10:45.194
ROWBY (Laughing): Costs? Oh. oh.
it's $3.1 million in costs?

293
00:10:45.224 --> 00:10:47.035
Promotional. touring...

294
00:10:47.065 --> 00:10:48.454
They didn't promote my album.

295
00:10:48.484 --> 00:10:50.193
...CD packaging and breakage.

296
00:10:50.223 --> 00:10:52.139
Almost everything was online.

297
00:10:52.169 --> 00:10:53.669
I mean. I don't... I don't...
I don't remember

298
00:10:53.699 --> 00:10:55.099
negotiating any of this stuff.

299
00:10:55.129 --> 00:10:56.139
You probably didn't.

300
00:10:56.169 --> 00:10:57.950
It's all pretty boiler-plate.

301
00:10:57.980 --> 00:10:59.517
It's designed to maximize their profits.

302
00:10:59.547 --> 00:11:01.950
- keep their artists indebted.
- Well. it's working.

303
00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:05.033
Now what? I mean. I-I can't
afford $3.1 million.

304
00:11:05.063 --> 00:11:06.779
It's ridiculous.

305
00:11:06.859 --> 00:11:08.371
Can you guys represent me?

306
00:11:11.072 --> 00:11:13.072
Well. we would have to talk about our fee.

307
00:11:13.102 --> 00:11:13.837
- Well. what if...
- (Doorbell rings)

308
00:11:13.867 --> 00:11:16.080
what if I just paid you back
with a percentage of the song?

309
00:11:16.110 --> 00:11:17.689
If you get it back.

310
00:11:18.132 --> 00:11:19.360
"If"?

311
00:11:21.393 --> 00:11:22.707
It's not about us.

312
00:11:23.101 --> 00:11:24.189
It's about work.

313
00:11:25.196 --> 00:11:27.529
I'm working as the chief
of staff for Peter now...

314
00:11:27.714 --> 00:11:30.529
again... and I wanted

315
00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:32.630
to talk to you about the future.

316
00:11:34.707 --> 00:11:36.597
Potential political problems.

317
00:11:36.627 --> 00:11:38.166
Not just...

318
00:11:43.858 --> 00:11:45.820
(Elevator bell dings)

319
00:11:55.436 --> 00:11:57.310
Oh. Hi. Mrs. Dosek. How are you?

320
00:11:57.340 --> 00:11:59.469
Fine. Can you give this
to your mother?

321
00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:01.280
Oh. Uh. yes. What is it?

322
00:12:01.310 --> 00:12:03.270
It's from the homeowners' association.

323
00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:04.879
It's an eviction notice.

324
00:12:06.217 --> 00:12:07.015
Excuse me?

325
00:12:07.045 --> 00:12:08.020
Your mother is running a business

326
00:12:08.050 --> 00:12:08.862
out of her home.

327
00:12:08.892 --> 00:12:09.614
No. she isn't.

328
00:12:09.644 --> 00:12:11.850
ROWBY: You know. just tell... you tell them

329
00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.290
that I'll see 'em in court.

330
00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:14.574
Excuse me.

331
00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:18.540
That's just a friend of the family.

332
00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:20.633
Your mother has one week to respond

333
00:12:20.663 --> 00:12:23.360
before we commence
eviction proceedings.

334
00:12:27.047 --> 00:12:34.699
= synced and corrected by Shahrazade =
... www.addic7ed.com ...

335
00:12:41.837 --> 00:12:43.753
I like this office.
Why are you leaving it?

336
00:12:43.783 --> 00:12:45.905
- Come on. I need the chair.
- No. I think you should stay here.

337
00:12:45.935 --> 00:12:46.792
It keeps you humble.

338
00:12:46.822 --> 00:12:48.675
Come on. I don't have time to play.

339
00:12:48.705 --> 00:12:51.149
Wow. you're sour.

340
00:12:51.179 --> 00:12:52.650
(Sighs)

341
00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:56.120
See? It's so impersonal in here.

342
00:12:56.863 --> 00:12:59.195
If you want the small
office. you can take it.

343
00:12:59.225 --> 00:13:00.725
- Uh-huh.
- Really?

344
00:13:01.087 --> 00:13:02.479
Really? I should take the small office?

345
00:13:02.776 --> 00:13:04.604
- I can have the job?
- What job?

346
00:13:04.634 --> 00:13:05.569
The job you're offering me.

347
00:13:05.599 --> 00:13:06.790
I am not offering you a job.

348
00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:08.649
There is no job. Can you see I'm busy?

349
00:13:08.679 --> 00:13:11.415
Dad. I need a job.
I need to finance my art.

350
00:13:11.445 --> 00:13:14.045
- What art?
- The art of living. Come on.

351
00:13:14.397 --> 00:13:16.239
ELI: I can't help you. Ask someone else.

352
00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:18.409
Ask Alicia.

353
00:13:18.797 --> 00:13:21.242
Yeah. Alicia. She probably needs someone.

354
00:13:21.272 --> 00:13:24.009
- Her firm just took on a lot of clients.
- Huh.

355
00:13:24.039 --> 00:13:25.539
It's not a bad idea.

356
00:13:25.742 --> 00:13:26.829
Odd.

357
00:13:27.395 --> 00:13:28.409
You know. you're not as fun

358
00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:31.402
as you used to be. Dad...
something's off with you.

359
00:13:31.432 --> 00:13:33.060
It's called fatherhood.

360
00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:34.108
DAMON: <i>The fact of the matter is</i>

361
00:13:34.138 --> 00:13:35.695
that Rowby Canton isn't

362
00:13:35.725 --> 00:13:37.125
a freedom fighter.

363
00:13:37.645 --> 00:13:39.289
He's a man under contract

364
00:13:39.290 --> 00:13:41.260
- who wishes he weren't.
- But Mr. Canton says

365
00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:42.990
he delivered you a second
album... didn't he?

366
00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:44.599
DAMON: Yes. but what he delivered

367
00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:46.226
was... unacceptable.

368
00:13:46.256 --> 00:13:48.599
Can I say something? Because that is r...

369
00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:49.878
- really offensive.
- JUDGE PAGE: No.

370
00:13:49.908 --> 00:13:51.689
Unfortunately not. Mr. Canton.

371
00:13:51.690 --> 00:13:53.455
ROWBY: Point of personal privilege.

372
00:13:53.485 --> 00:13:56.430
Yes. I'm guessing that you saw
that in a movie. sir.

373
00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:57.809
That doesn't work here.

374
00:13:57.810 --> 00:13:59.519
- Please continue.
- Thank you. Your Honor.

375
00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:01.263
- Mr. Stryk.
- There were no crowd-pleasers.

376
00:14:01.293 --> 00:14:03.700
there were no hooks. there was
nothing I could even repackage

377
00:14:03.730 --> 00:14:05.269
to any other artist.

378
00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:06.889
(Quietly): I already reposted it.

379
00:14:07.542 --> 00:14:08.479
LUCCA: How did you do that?

380
00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:09.759
I thought they had it excluded.

381
00:14:09.789 --> 00:14:10.860
Mirror-reversed it.

382
00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:12.889
The classic way to get around
their detection software.

383
00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:14.466
How long before you think
they figure it out?

384
00:14:14.496 --> 00:14:15.979
DAMON: I have produced

385
00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:17.809
over 200 of them.

386
00:14:17.810 --> 00:14:21.491
And what Mr. Canton
handed me was... not a hit.

387
00:14:21.521 --> 00:14:24.019
ANDREA: Your Honor. I know it's
hard for artists like Rowby.

388
00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:27.099
who tend to work from an
emotional place. to understand

389
00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:30.077
- all the ins and outs...
- Objection. Your Honor.

390
00:14:30.107 --> 00:14:31.246
Counsel is testifying.

391
00:14:31.276 --> 00:14:33.429
No. I'm just trying
to be compassionate. but...

392
00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:34.929
I'll hold my tongue.

393
00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:36.929
(Softly): I seem to have touched
on a sensitive area.

394
00:14:38.071 --> 00:14:39.389
Mr. Stryk... (sighs)

395
00:14:39.799 --> 00:14:41.769
you keep talking about hit records.

396
00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:43.743
but Rowby wasn't contractually obligated

397
00:14:43.773 --> 00:14:44.889
to deliver a hit album.

398
00:14:44.890 --> 00:14:47.139
- That's true.
- He was obligated to deliver an album

399
00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:48.696
that was "substantially similar

400
00:14:48.726 --> 00:14:52.154
in quality and genre
to artist's initial album."

401
00:14:52.184 --> 00:14:53.057
Is that true. too?

402
00:14:53.087 --> 00:14:54.718
- It is.
- No further questions. Your Honor.

403
00:14:54.748 --> 00:14:56.457
- Ms. Stevens. anything?
- Yes.

404
00:14:56.487 --> 00:14:57.738
Thank you. Your Honor.

405
00:14:57.768 --> 00:14:59.645
Was Mr. Canton's second album

406
00:14:59.675 --> 00:15:02.682
"substantially similar in
quality and genre" to his first?

407
00:15:02.712 --> 00:15:05.224
- No. it was not.
- Why not?

408
00:15:05.254 --> 00:15:09.068
Because his first album
wasn't substantially bad.

409
00:15:09.098 --> 00:15:11.139
- Objection. Prejudicial.
- Objection!

410
00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:13.099
PAGE:
Sustained.

411
00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:14.672
Yeah. Sustained.

412
00:15:14.702 --> 00:15:17.357
Mr. Canton. I'm extending you a little rope

413
00:15:17.387 --> 00:15:19.664
because I find you entertaining.

414
00:15:19.694 --> 00:15:21.803
- Don't push it.
- I'm sorry. Your Honor.

415
00:15:21.833 --> 00:15:23.850
MAN: Andrea. the video's back up.

416
00:15:27.496 --> 00:15:28.796
<i>(Doorbell rings)</i>

417
00:15:30.318 --> 00:15:32.479
Wow. you have a bitch
of a neighbor downstairs.

418
00:15:32.671 --> 00:15:34.639
Yeah. I know.
She's not happy with us.

419
00:15:35.125 --> 00:15:36.277
- May I help you?
- Marissa.

420
00:15:36.307 --> 00:15:38.309
Remember? Eli's funny daughter.

421
00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:39.292
I'm here to see your mom.

422
00:15:39.322 --> 00:15:41.296
Oh. she'll be back from court in. like. a minute.

423
00:15:41.326 --> 00:15:42.559
Can I wait?

424
00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:46.099
Oh. and the bitch gave me this.

425
00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:47.640
She's trying to evict us.

426
00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:49.572
Homeowners' association?

427
00:15:49.602 --> 00:15:51.999
Yeah. We're not supposed
to have a home office.

428
00:15:52.246 --> 00:15:53.999
Does anybody have a home office?

429
00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.419
In the building?

430
00:15:55.420 --> 00:15:56.999
Yeah. I think so. Why?

431
00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.163
You should check.

432
00:15:58.193 --> 00:16:00.039
All these homeowners'
association people think

433
00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:01.050
they're above the law.

434
00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:02.669
Usually they're just as corrupt.

435
00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:03.626
How do I check?

436
00:16:03.656 --> 00:16:05.020
Sit down in the lobby.

437
00:16:05.050 --> 00:16:07.589
Wait for a UPS man or a FedEx man to come.

438
00:16:07.590 --> 00:16:09.690
then follow him up to the floor.

439
00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:13.459
Whoever gets the most packages.
they have the home offices.

440
00:16:13.951 --> 00:16:15.714
I know. It's my dad's genes.

441
00:16:15.744 --> 00:16:17.162
- Very sneaky.
- (Door opens)

442
00:16:17.192 --> 00:16:18.580
Hey. Mom. we're in here.

443
00:16:22.109 --> 00:16:24.380
- Marissa. hi.
- Hi.

444
00:16:24.977 --> 00:16:26.788
I'm back in your life again.

445
00:16:26.818 --> 00:16:29.119
So where were you? Were you back in Israel?

446
00:16:29.149 --> 00:16:30.789
No. San Francisco.

447
00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:32.829
No reason. Someone bet me.

448
00:16:32.859 --> 00:16:34.714
- I need a job.
- Okay.

449
00:16:34.744 --> 00:16:37.499
And I wanted to give you
first shot at hiring me.

450
00:16:38.111 --> 00:16:39.089
(Laughs)

451
00:16:39.433 --> 00:16:41.879
Thank you. uh. but I don't need anyone now.

452
00:16:42.148 --> 00:16:45.169
Dad said you were taking
on all these new clients.

453
00:16:45.677 --> 00:16:46.677
Ah.

454
00:16:46.943 --> 00:16:47.851
Eli told you that?

455
00:16:47.881 --> 00:16:49.919
Yeah. He said you might need someone.

456
00:16:50.391 --> 00:16:51.879
No. I'm good.

457
00:16:52.751 --> 00:16:55.129
Okay. Will you keep me
in mind if things change?

458
00:16:55.285 --> 00:16:57.379
Sure. but I don't think they will.

459
00:16:58.030 --> 00:16:59.030
Okay.

460
00:17:00.189 --> 00:17:01.269
Is everything all right?

461
00:17:01.299 --> 00:17:02.799
Yes. I just don't...

462
00:17:04.533 --> 00:17:05.919
Tell Eli to stop it.

463
00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:07.106
Stop what?

464
00:17:07.136 --> 00:17:12.132
Marissa. visit me because you want to.
not because your dad wants you to.

465
00:17:12.162 --> 00:17:13.962
I did because I wanted to.

466
00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:17.790
Well. I have
to get back to court.

467
00:17:17.820 --> 00:17:19.360
Good seeing you again. Marissa.

468
00:17:20.650 --> 00:17:21.650
Same here.

469
00:17:23.700 --> 00:17:24.717
MAN: <i>Morris Weiner.</i>

470
00:17:24.747 --> 00:17:27.149
PhD. I hold the Pederson Chair

471
00:17:27.150 --> 00:17:29.122
of Musicology at Ridgeton.

472
00:17:29.152 --> 00:17:30.882
Doctor. what is pop music?

473
00:17:30.912 --> 00:17:32.604
A genre of popular music

474
00:17:32.634 --> 00:17:34.587
based in rock and roll
of the '50s and '60s.

475
00:17:34.617 --> 00:17:36.024
And how would you recognize a pop song?

476
00:17:36.054 --> 00:17:37.439
Through its hooks.

477
00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:39.029
Pop songs are all full of hooks.

478
00:17:39.030 --> 00:17:40.229
There's one in the intro.

479
00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:41.569
another in the chorus.

480
00:17:41.570 --> 00:17:42.540
there's another in the bridge.

481
00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:43.597
And what do you mean by "hook"?

482
00:17:43.627 --> 00:17:46.747
It's a short. catchy. repeated riff.

483
00:17:46.777 --> 00:17:47.744
It's an earworm.

484
00:17:47.774 --> 00:17:49.466
ANDREA: And that's all
there is to it? The hooks?

485
00:17:49.496 --> 00:17:52.689
No. uh. pop songs also tend
to be nonharmonic

486
00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:55.404
with pronounced timbral dissonance.

487
00:17:55.434 --> 00:17:57.399
Four-bar phrasing. a beat-per-minute range

488
00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:00.029
between 72 and 85.

489
00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:01.569
ANDREA: So you're saying
that Rowby Canton's

490
00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:04.106
new album didn't have
most of these hallmarks?

491
00:18:04.136 --> 00:18:06.804
I'm saying it had none of them. Listen.

492
00:18:07.489 --> 00:18:11.439
♪ I saw a light I'd never seen before... ♪

493
00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:12.718
ANDREA: Yes. yes. you're right.

494
00:18:12.748 --> 00:18:14.859
It's-it's not as catchy. is it?

495
00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:16.939
I keep trying to tap my foot. but...

496
00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:18.942
This was not substantially similar

497
00:18:18.972 --> 00:18:22.109
- to his first album.
- Thank you. No further questions.

498
00:18:23.150 --> 00:18:24.529
"Bohemian Rhapsody."

499
00:18:24.530 --> 00:18:26.969
The song by Queen. You're familiar with it?

500
00:18:26.999 --> 00:18:28.566
- Of course.
- And you call that good?

501
00:18:28.596 --> 00:18:30.529
Right? A pop hit?

502
00:18:30.530 --> 00:18:32.734
Well... I would.

503
00:18:32.764 --> 00:18:34.939
Well. yeah. it-it is. It's a pop hit.

504
00:18:34.940 --> 00:18:36.489
Could you point out where the hooks are?

505
00:18:36.490 --> 00:18:39.057
Well. you know.
not all pop songs are identical.

506
00:18:39.087 --> 00:18:41.260
Oh. Well. can I read back

507
00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:43.397
your testimony from a few minutes ago?

508
00:18:43.427 --> 00:18:45.939
"Pop songs are all full of hooks."

509
00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:47.729
- Oh. Lucca. I love you.
- (Gavel slams)

510
00:18:47.730 --> 00:18:50.080
LUCCA: Would you like to correct
your testimony. sir?

511
00:18:50.415 --> 00:18:53.860
Not <i>all </i>pop songs are identical.
Most are identical.

512
00:18:53.890 --> 00:18:54.890
Yeah...

513
00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:57.155
Uh. sorry. I-I don't thinkwe caught that.

514
00:18:57.185 --> 00:18:58.700
Right into your microphone there.

515
00:18:58.730 --> 00:19:00.389
Yes. not all pop songs.

516
00:19:00.419 --> 00:19:03.009
And could you tell us where
the four-bar phrases are

517
00:19:03.010 --> 00:19:04.469
and the chorus and the verse?

518
00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:05.518
WEINER: Well. that's
difficult to distinguish.

519
00:19:05.548 --> 00:19:07.877
LUCCA: And the 72 to 85
beats-per-minute range... where's that?

520
00:19:07.907 --> 00:19:08.753
Yeah. but again.

521
00:19:08.783 --> 00:19:10.801
"Bohemian Rhapsody" is an unusual case.

522
00:19:10.831 --> 00:19:13.065
As is Rowby's song. Thank you.

523
00:19:13.095 --> 00:19:14.442
ANDREA: Mm. That last little bit

524
00:19:14.472 --> 00:19:16.629
wasn't really a question. was it?

525
00:19:16.630 --> 00:19:18.125
Yeah. let me see if I can confine

526
00:19:18.155 --> 00:19:20.009
my redirect to questions.

527
00:19:20.039 --> 00:19:21.636
Mr. Canton's contract said

528
00:19:21.666 --> 00:19:24.603
"substantially similar in quality and genre."

529
00:19:24.633 --> 00:19:25.987
What genre was his first album?

530
00:19:26.017 --> 00:19:28.969
- As I've said. it was pop.
- And...

531
00:19:28.970 --> 00:19:31.589
what is... this?

532
00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:34.121
♪ I saw the light... ♪

533
00:19:34.151 --> 00:19:35.839
- It-it's not pop.
- Thank you.

534
00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:38.150
And I love "Bohemian Rhapsody." too.

535
00:19:38.451 --> 00:19:40.905
♪ I couldn't stare... ♪

536
00:19:40.935 --> 00:19:42.589
Kermit Corriel.

537
00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:44.017
I taught music at Juilliard.

538
00:19:44.047 --> 00:19:46.106
You also have a doctorate
in musicology from Juilliard?

539
00:19:46.136 --> 00:19:49.469
Well. yeah. but who goes around
advertising that?

540
00:19:49.470 --> 00:19:50.693
This guy is awesome.

541
00:19:50.723 --> 00:19:52.090
CARY: Would you agree
that Rowby's second album

542
00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:54.259
is not in the same pop genre
as his first album?

543
00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:56.272
I don't think I'd agree
with any part of that.

544
00:19:56.302 --> 00:19:58.881
His first album wasn't exactly 100% pop.

545
00:19:58.911 --> 00:20:01.029
And I don't think his second
album's all that different.

546
00:20:01.059 --> 00:20:01.669
Can you explain?

547
00:20:01.699 --> 00:20:04.009
Well. yeah. I mean.
genres aren't fixed. right?

548
00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:05.839
They ebb and flow over time.

549
00:20:05.840 --> 00:20:08.271
And then there's this give
and take between genres.

550
00:20:08.301 --> 00:20:10.219
Like. Rowby's first album was pop.

551
00:20:10.393 --> 00:20:13.173
but it also had country
and folk tendencies. too.

552
00:20:13.203 --> 00:20:15.129
- And his second album?
- Well. that pushes deeper into country.

553
00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:16.535
You can hear that in the intro.

554
00:20:16.565 --> 00:20:18.049
And then it pushes further into folk

555
00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:19.629
with the verse. and then in the chorus.

556
00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.824
I mean. look. it's pretty clear
that it's indie pop.

557
00:20:21.854 --> 00:20:24.118
So. is this the same or
different than "Thicky Trick"?

558
00:20:24.148 --> 00:20:26.429
I don't know... it-it-it's both. man.

559
00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:27.933
Rowby's an artist.

560
00:20:27.963 --> 00:20:28.743
He's exploring.

561
00:20:28.773 --> 00:20:30.710
Both those songs are written
by the same person.

562
00:20:30.740 --> 00:20:31.939
but they're not identical.

563
00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:33.328
And no album
should be identical.

564
00:20:33.395 --> 00:20:35.099
Like Picasso. right?

565
00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:37.688
You see him going through his
Blue Period or his Crystal Period.

566
00:20:37.718 --> 00:20:41.120
- Thank you.
- PAGE: Okay. this is all fascinating.

567
00:20:41.150 --> 00:20:43.148
but there's nothing that I've heard

568
00:20:43.178 --> 00:20:45.539
that convinces me that
there's anything close

569
00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:48.390
to objective truth here. so I have to defer

570
00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:50.232
to the good faith efforts

571
00:20:50.262 --> 00:20:53.127
made by Mr. Canton to fulfill his contract.

572
00:20:53.157 --> 00:20:55.653
Yes. Your Honor. you...

573
00:20:55.683 --> 00:20:56.615
are awesome. thank you.

574
00:20:56.645 --> 00:20:58.700
Your Honor. uh. we seek lead to argue

575
00:20:58.730 --> 00:20:59.878
that the song was written

576
00:20:59.908 --> 00:21:02.168
during the term of his contract.

577
00:21:02.198 --> 00:21:04.138
- What?
- You do?

578
00:21:04.572 --> 00:21:07.110
Then why did we go through this exercise?

579
00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:08.268
I'm so sorry. Your Honor.

580
00:21:08.298 --> 00:21:10.153
but this was just brought to our attention.

581
00:21:10.183 --> 00:21:13.563
This is another video that Mr. Canton

582
00:21:13.593 --> 00:21:15.349
posted online.

583
00:21:15.350 --> 00:21:17.559
♪ ♪

584
00:21:17.560 --> 00:21:19.929
♪ Good morning. magic sunshine ♪

585
00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:22.969
♪ It's a brand-new day... ♪

586
00:21:23.672 --> 00:21:24.513
PAGE: Very nice.

587
00:21:24.543 --> 00:21:25.463
What am I looking for?

588
00:21:25.493 --> 00:21:27.148
The time code stamp.

589
00:21:27.178 --> 00:21:29.929
ChummyVideo stamps the
posting time of all videos.

590
00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:32.849
See. this video was posted at 11:42 p.m.

591
00:21:32.850 --> 00:21:34.639
on November 30.

592
00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:37.568
Rowby Canton's contract didn't expire

593
00:21:37.598 --> 00:21:39.710
until midnight on that date. Your Honor.

594
00:21:39.740 --> 00:21:43.639
Therefore. he wrote the song
while still under contract.

595
00:21:44.007 --> 00:21:48.237
♪ Wake up and start my day
with magic sunsh... ♪

596
00:21:58.245 --> 00:21:59.876
What's going on with you and Alicia?

597
00:21:59.906 --> 00:22:01.546
Nothing. Can we not do this now?

598
00:22:01.576 --> 00:22:02.673
No. we're doing this now. Dad.

599
00:22:02.703 --> 00:22:04.579
You got Mom pregnant.
so we're doing this now.

600
00:22:04.580 --> 00:22:06.179
What did Alicia say?

601
00:22:06.209 --> 00:22:08.002
She said. "Tell Eli to stop it."

602
00:22:08.032 --> 00:22:08.653
Stop what?

603
00:22:08.683 --> 00:22:10.983
That's what I asked. She didn't say.

604
00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:13.890
She made it sound like
she didn't have to say.

605
00:22:18.887 --> 00:22:22.767
Alicia and I are having some... issues.

606
00:22:22.797 --> 00:22:24.109
Are you sleeping with her?

607
00:22:24.110 --> 00:22:26.149
Oh. my God. no!

608
00:22:26.327 --> 00:22:27.359
No.

609
00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:28.390
Are you wanting to?

610
00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:30.432
What? No.

611
00:22:30.462 --> 00:22:32.456
It's nothing like that.

612
00:22:32.486 --> 00:22:34.150
Then what is it?

613
00:22:36.319 --> 00:22:37.661
Uh...

614
00:22:37.691 --> 00:22:40.319
Six years ago. Alicia got a voice mail

615
00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:42.939
from... a friend.

616
00:22:43.562 --> 00:22:44.945
someone who was in love with her.

617
00:22:44.975 --> 00:22:45.975
Will?

618
00:22:46.845 --> 00:22:47.740
Yes. How do you know that?

619
00:22:47.770 --> 00:22:48.870
I have eyes.

620
00:22:50.454 --> 00:22:51.729
And he said that he loved her.

621
00:22:51.730 --> 00:22:55.519
and I was worried about
Alicia getting this voice mail

622
00:22:55.520 --> 00:22:58.229
in the middle of a campaign. so...

623
00:22:58.884 --> 00:23:00.230
I erased it.

624
00:23:03.595 --> 00:23:06.319
And I felt bad about it. and so I told her.

625
00:23:06.648 --> 00:23:07.720
When?

626
00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:08.800
A week ago.

627
00:23:10.181 --> 00:23:11.520
And that's it.

628
00:23:12.845 --> 00:23:16.229
So he called her and said. "I
love you." and you erased it?

629
00:23:16.230 --> 00:23:17.796
And now Will's gone. and it's something

630
00:23:17.826 --> 00:23:19.359
she can never make right.

631
00:23:19.851 --> 00:23:20.851
Yes.

632
00:23:21.868 --> 00:23:23.149
I'm not proud of it.

633
00:23:23.150 --> 00:23:25.979
That's why I told her.

634
00:23:27.327 --> 00:23:29.214
God. it's like a soap
opera here when I'm gone.

635
00:23:29.244 --> 00:23:30.552
And now she's gonna think
I'm trying to get back

636
00:23:30.582 --> 00:23:32.519
into her good graces by
sending you over there.

637
00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:33.989
- She won't talk to you?
- No.

638
00:23:34.019 --> 00:23:35.589
- You think that'll change?
- No.

639
00:23:35.619 --> 00:23:37.610
- Have you tried...
- Yes. yes.

640
00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:39.180
Everything.

641
00:23:42.706 --> 00:23:43.889
What are you doing?

642
00:23:44.157 --> 00:23:45.472
I don't know. I have to think about it.

643
00:23:45.502 --> 00:23:47.099
Just-just don't do anything. okay?

644
00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:48.792
- This is my thing.
- All right. Bye.

645
00:23:48.822 --> 00:23:49.861
You're gonna do something.

646
00:23:49.891 --> 00:23:51.783
- aren't you? Marissa.
- (Door closes)

647
00:23:52.786 --> 00:23:53.938
ALICIA: <i>Andrea Stevens</i>

648
00:23:53.968 --> 00:23:55.830
has subpoenaed your computer

649
00:23:55.860 --> 00:23:58.024
and your phone. so we need to know:

650
00:23:58.054 --> 00:24:00.290
Did you write "Good Morning Magic Sunshine"

651
00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:03.279
while you were under contract for G.F.C?

652
00:24:03.663 --> 00:24:05.579
- No.
- ChummyVideo time-stamps

653
00:24:05.580 --> 00:24:08.319
every posting. and we've
confirmed you posted the song

654
00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:10.516
at 11:42 p.m. on the 30th.

655
00:24:10.546 --> 00:24:13.214
- which means the contract was still valid.
- LUCCA: Wait.

656
00:24:13.244 --> 00:24:15.146
Where is ChummyVideo centered?

657
00:24:15.176 --> 00:24:16.950
- What do you mean?
- Well. it's California.

658
00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:18.542
right? It's a California company.

659
00:24:18.572 --> 00:24:20.489
That's right. That's right.

660
00:24:20.490 --> 00:24:22.705
Lucca. that's-that's totally right!

661
00:24:22.735 --> 00:24:24.210
Are you saying the time
zone made a difference?

662
00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:25.912
Yes. I posted the video

663
00:24:25.942 --> 00:24:27.908
at 11:42 p.m.

664
00:24:27.938 --> 00:24:29.838
Pacific time. which means...

665
00:24:31.705 --> 00:24:33.047
1:42 a.m. Chicago time.

666
00:24:33.077 --> 00:24:35.234
Yeah. which means the contract's expired.

667
00:24:35.264 --> 00:24:37.234
Yeah. but you wrote the
song in that short of a time?

668
00:24:37.264 --> 00:24:40.098
Yes. that's how all of my songs
come. Trust me when I say

669
00:24:40.128 --> 00:24:42.159
I know when the damn contract ended.

670
00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:44.817
And the minute the clock
struck midnight. I celebrated.

671
00:24:44.847 --> 00:24:47.203
I had people over to my house.

672
00:24:47.233 --> 00:24:49.199
Unfortunately. I woke up my son.

673
00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:50.533
and I tried to get him to go back to sleep.

674
00:24:50.563 --> 00:24:53.564
and when it didn't work. I wrote
"Good Morning Magic Sunshine."

675
00:24:53.594 --> 00:24:55.588
You improvised it on video?

676
00:24:55.618 --> 00:24:57.378
Yeah. it's pretty cool. right?

677
00:24:57.408 --> 00:24:58.557
I keep telling you guys. it's just

678
00:24:58.587 --> 00:25:00.620
a song I wrote for my kid.

679
00:25:06.419 --> 00:25:09.308
I would really like to buy you a drink.

680
00:25:09.338 --> 00:25:10.423
Why?

681
00:25:10.453 --> 00:25:12.153
Because you are awesome.

682
00:25:13.030 --> 00:25:14.700
How long have you been married. Rowby?

683
00:25:14.730 --> 00:25:15.883
I've never been married.

684
00:25:15.913 --> 00:25:17.363
I wrote you a song.

685
00:25:18.618 --> 00:25:20.618
So who was holding the camera?

686
00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:22.380
What camera?

687
00:25:23.180 --> 00:25:25.319
When you were playing for your son?

688
00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:27.384
You were playing the
guitar. your son was in bed.

689
00:25:27.414 --> 00:25:29.069
and someone was holding the camera.

690
00:25:29.099 --> 00:25:30.249
Who was that?

691
00:25:32.658 --> 00:25:34.409
We're divorced.

692
00:25:34.879 --> 00:25:37.143
She wanted a two-car garage.

693
00:25:37.173 --> 00:25:40.530
and... I couldn't give it to her.

694
00:25:41.884 --> 00:25:42.934
True story.

695
00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:50.820
♪ ♪

696
00:25:52.656 --> 00:25:54.819
(Chuckling): You're like a Bond girl.

697
00:25:55.178 --> 00:25:57.906
I like artists.

698
00:25:59.516 --> 00:26:03.449
but I lose interest in them real quick.

699
00:26:04.651 --> 00:26:06.151
You want to go home?

700
00:26:07.028 --> 00:26:09.319
Sure. I have a babysitter.

701
00:26:09.518 --> 00:26:11.484
Is your home an artist's hovel?

702
00:26:11.514 --> 00:26:14.370
Yes. but tomorrow's cleaning day.

703
00:26:15.128 --> 00:26:16.782
My apartment.

704
00:26:16.812 --> 00:26:18.545
Just for an hour.

705
00:26:19.087 --> 00:26:20.162
Then you'll go home.

706
00:26:20.192 --> 00:26:21.192
I promise.

707
00:26:23.378 --> 00:26:26.319
It was just. like... boom!

708
00:26:26.320 --> 00:26:29.409
It wasn't there. and then
all of a sudden. it was there.

709
00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:32.829
It was. uh. like. this-this.
um. like. creative orgasm.

710
00:26:32.859 --> 00:26:35.579
ALICIA: Like a burst of creativity.

711
00:26:35.950 --> 00:26:38.120
Yes. like a... yes.

712
00:26:38.150 --> 00:26:39.642
And I just. I sat there.

713
00:26:39.672 --> 00:26:41.323
and I just watched the clock

714
00:26:41.353 --> 00:26:43.358
until my contract expired.

715
00:26:43.388 --> 00:26:45.279
and then I was like. bang.
bang. bang. bang. bang. bang.

716
00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:48.726
And I wrote. like. eight songs.
one after another. like. boom.

717
00:26:48.756 --> 00:26:51.639
ALICIA: And is that common
to be able to generate

718
00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:53.794
a good. quality song in
such a short amount of time?

719
00:26:53.824 --> 00:26:57.219
The song "Yesterday." McCartney
woke up with that in his head.

720
00:26:57.220 --> 00:26:59.311
- Thank you.
- Mr. Canton. do you mind if I ask.

721
00:26:59.341 --> 00:27:00.720
how long did it take you to write

722
00:27:00.750 --> 00:27:02.999
the eight songs for your second album?

723
00:27:03.029 --> 00:27:05.734
- I don't know. Years?
- ANDREA: Two years. actually.

724
00:27:05.764 --> 00:27:08.579
So it took two years for eight songs.

725
00:27:08.580 --> 00:27:11.346
and then. let's see. two
hours for the next eight?

726
00:27:11.376 --> 00:27:12.879
I was just under a lot of pressure

727
00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:14.265
to write the first eight songs.

728
00:27:14.295 --> 00:27:17.039
My goodness. that must be
quite a bit of pressure for you.

729
00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.047
- Objection. Your Honor.
- I withdraw that. It's not a big point.

730
00:27:20.077 --> 00:27:22.176
So can you help me understand

731
00:27:22.206 --> 00:27:24.769
this note you left on
your subpoenaed smartphone?

732
00:27:24.799 --> 00:27:27.499
It's a lyric from "Good
Morning Magic Sunshine."

733
00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:29.709
It says. "Make me warm and toasty

734
00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:32.249
while I lay here warm and cozy."

735
00:27:32.250 --> 00:27:36.048
and it's dated 23 days before
the end of your record contract.

736
00:27:36.078 --> 00:27:37.782
ROWBY: Uh. I wrote that
down. but that's not a lyric.

737
00:27:37.812 --> 00:27:38.835
ANDREA: I'm pretty sure it is.

738
00:27:38.865 --> 00:27:40.278
No. it ended up as a lyric.

739
00:27:40.308 --> 00:27:42.674
It's just. it's something that my son said.

740
00:27:42.704 --> 00:27:45.488
Like. he said something
totally cute and awesome.

741
00:27:45.518 --> 00:27:46.476
and I wrote it down.

742
00:27:46.506 --> 00:27:49.289
Which. according to the terms
of your deal with G.F.C Records.

743
00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:51.040
constitutes work product

744
00:27:51.070 --> 00:27:52.790
created within the term of your contract.

745
00:27:52.820 --> 00:27:55.156
You're claiming that you own
the copyright to that line?

746
00:27:55.186 --> 00:27:57.865
- Absolutely.
- Uh. that's absurd on its face.

747
00:27:57.895 --> 00:27:59.679
They don't own everything his kid says

748
00:27:59.709 --> 00:28:01.693
- just because he wrote it down.
- I didn't say "everything."

749
00:28:01.723 --> 00:28:02.877
- Are you seriously...?
- Well. that's...

750
00:28:02.907 --> 00:28:04.980
I mean. his son... his son...

751
00:28:05.010 --> 00:28:06.449
His son. Your Honor.

752
00:28:06.479 --> 00:28:10.044
his son. Josh's quote was not work product.

753
00:28:10.074 --> 00:28:11.413
Your Honor. it was inspiration.

754
00:28:11.443 --> 00:28:13.676
"Inspiration" isn't a legal term.

755
00:28:13.706 --> 00:28:15.040
It's an artistic conceit.

756
00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:16.866
- Because Rowby is an artist.
- An artist under contract.

757
00:28:16.896 --> 00:28:19.851
But Rowby's contract does not
negate the creative process.

758
00:28:19.881 --> 00:28:21.989
He wrote something down
that was meaningful to him.

759
00:28:21.990 --> 00:28:23.792
not knowing it would
make its way into a song.

760
00:28:23.822 --> 00:28:25.463
But it did. quite directly.

761
00:28:25.493 --> 00:28:28.409
Josh's quote was the first
step in a songwriting process

762
00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:32.199
that Mr. Canton began while
still under a deal with G.F.C.

763
00:28:32.200 --> 00:28:34.319
ALICIA: Think about what
she's saying. Your Honor.

764
00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:37.525
A.A. Milne based
Christopher Robin on his son.

765
00:28:37.555 --> 00:28:39.869
but that doesn't mean he started
writing <i>Winnie-the-Pooh</i>

766
00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:41.659
the day he became a father.

767
00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:43.949
Bob Dylan didn't start
writing "Tangled Up in Blue"

768
00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.341
on the day of his marriage even
though that's what it's about.

769
00:28:46.371 --> 00:28:49.473
Those were general inspirations;
this is a specific line.

770
00:28:49.503 --> 00:28:51.497
- No. it became a specific line.
- Moreover. the existence

771
00:28:51.527 --> 00:28:54.158
of this note undercuts
Mr. Canton's claim that he wrote

772
00:28:54.188 --> 00:28:55.991
"Good Morning Magic
Sunshine" in less than a day.

773
00:28:56.021 --> 00:28:59.103
The act of observing the world
is not the same as composing.

774
00:28:59.133 --> 00:29:01.159
Enough. please.

775
00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:05.239
Um. your cynicism is. I'm sure. warranted.

776
00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:06.832
given your business. Miss Stevens.

777
00:29:06.862 --> 00:29:09.369
but I-I must agree
with the defendant here.

778
00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:13.062
Observing the world is
not the same as composing.

779
00:29:13.092 --> 00:29:16.715
I don't think any of us want to
slide down that slippery slope.

780
00:29:16.745 --> 00:29:18.450
- (Gavel slams)
- Case dismissed.

781
00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:21.814
Did we... did we just win?

782
00:29:21.844 --> 00:29:23.689
- You won.
- We won?! Yes.

783
00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:25.970
We did it.

784
00:29:29.870 --> 00:29:31.722
DOSEK: <i>And I'm constantly
signing for her packages.</i>

785
00:29:31.752 --> 00:29:34.199
and not for her personally;
for her business.

786
00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:35.440
I-I'm sorry. but I understood

787
00:29:35.470 --> 00:29:37.619
that Mrs. Florrick would be
present for today's meeting.

788
00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:39.421
Uh. Mrs. Florrick is otherwise
disposed at the moment.

789
00:29:39.451 --> 00:29:40.766
but as an employee of Florrick/Quinn.

790
00:29:40.796 --> 00:29:42.027
I can answer any questions you might have.

791
00:29:42.057 --> 00:29:43.007
Aren't you her daughter?

792
00:29:43.037 --> 00:29:44.200
Yes. I'm also an employee.

793
00:29:44.230 --> 00:29:45.489
DOSEK: Oh. so you admit that she is running

794
00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:47.990
- a business from her apartment.
- Yes.

795
00:29:48.214 --> 00:29:50.564
Well. that's against HOA regulations.

796
00:29:50.899 --> 00:29:52.406
- Is it?
- Yes. it is. Now...

797
00:29:52.436 --> 00:29:55.613
Well. then why isn't Mr.
Tipton being questioned?

798
00:29:55.643 --> 00:29:57.409
- MAN: I don't follow.
- GRACE: Mr. Graham Tipton.

799
00:29:57.410 --> 00:29:59.451
He runs a business out of his
apartment on the sixth floor.

800
00:29:59.481 --> 00:30:00.476
- Why isn't he...?
- I do not.

801
00:30:00.506 --> 00:30:01.741
Well. you're a day trader. aren't you?

802
00:30:01.771 --> 00:30:02.703
You work out of your apartment?

803
00:30:02.733 --> 00:30:05.171
I work from home. That's different than
running a business out of my apartment.

804
00:30:05.201 --> 00:30:07.819
But your loan-out company.
Graham Is Awesome. Inc..

805
00:30:07.820 --> 00:30:09.653
lists this building as its address.

806
00:30:09.683 --> 00:30:11.500
and your business receives its mail here.

807
00:30:11.530 --> 00:30:13.006
Are you always available to sign for it?

808
00:30:13.036 --> 00:30:16.186
- No. but...
- Okay. look. we are not on trial here.

809
00:30:16.492 --> 00:30:18.768
The regulations also prohibit subletting.

810
00:30:18.798 --> 00:30:20.899
but Mrs. Dosek rents a spare bedroom

811
00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:22.584
in her apartment to
her mother-in-law.

812
00:30:22.614 --> 00:30:25.848
Well. that's my mother-in-law.
There's an exemption for family.

813
00:30:25.878 --> 00:30:27.319
Actually. there isn't.

814
00:30:27.538 --> 00:30:30.319
Then there's Mr. Loring
on the eighth floor.

815
00:30:30.474 --> 00:30:32.116
who frequently hosts
high-priced call girls.

816
00:30:32.146 --> 00:30:34.570
Okay. okay. maybe we should just

817
00:30:34.600 --> 00:30:36.455
table this discussion for the moment.

818
00:30:36.485 --> 00:30:37.560
GRACE: I think that'd be good.

819
00:30:37.590 --> 00:30:39.180
My mother's a great lawyer.

820
00:30:39.210 --> 00:30:41.441
She usually stands up well for herself.

821
00:30:41.471 --> 00:30:44.437
ROWDY: ♪ 'Cause I don't want
to look back and wonder ♪

822
00:30:44.467 --> 00:30:48.379
♪ What if I'd called your name? ♪

823
00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:50.169
(Cell phone chimes)

824
00:30:50.170 --> 00:30:53.332
♪ So won't you tell me. Lucca... ♪

825
00:30:53.362 --> 00:30:55.169
Oh. no.

826
00:30:55.394 --> 00:30:56.419
I'm singing my heart out.

827
00:30:56.420 --> 00:30:58.960
How can you answer a text?

828
00:31:00.903 --> 00:31:02.303
You're being sued.

829
00:31:02.484 --> 00:31:03.243
Again?

830
00:31:03.273 --> 00:31:05.961
The label is suing you
for copyright infringement.

831
00:31:05.991 --> 00:31:06.978
Of what?

832
00:31:07.008 --> 00:31:08.839
Another kids' song they own.

833
00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:10.549
"Moony Moonikins."

834
00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:12.589
$2.8 million in damages.

835
00:31:12.590 --> 00:31:13.879
(Scoffs)

836
00:31:14.452 --> 00:31:15.879
My God.

837
00:31:16.293 --> 00:31:19.379
The law just gives so many
people ways to be mean.

838
00:31:20.041 --> 00:31:21.591
You gonna protect me?

839
00:31:21.624 --> 00:31:22.824
Doing my best.

840
00:31:29.880 --> 00:31:33.192
So let's talk about "Moony
Moonikins." You've heard it?

841
00:31:33.222 --> 00:31:34.470
Oh. yeah. of course.

842
00:31:34.499 --> 00:31:36.440
You've even played it
in your children's sets.

843
00:31:36.470 --> 00:31:37.919
I usually open my sets with it.

844
00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:39.919
It's. like. every kid's favorite song.

845
00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:44.106
Yeah. my adopted daughter
from China. she just adores it.

846
00:31:44.136 --> 00:31:45.800
Uh. tell me. how did this work?

847
00:31:45.830 --> 00:31:48.290
Did you just decide to change it a bit

848
00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:49.453
and then put your name on it. or...?

849
00:31:49.483 --> 00:31:51.491
No. look. if there's any similarities

850
00:31:51.521 --> 00:31:54.250
between the two songs. it's
'cause they're both kids songs.

851
00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:55.939
You know. when you're working with kids

852
00:31:55.940 --> 00:31:57.479
with a shorter attention span.

853
00:31:57.480 --> 00:31:59.367
and there's no sex.
drugs. and rock and roll.

854
00:31:59.397 --> 00:32:01.201
you're somewhat narrowing your sandbox.

855
00:32:01.231 --> 00:32:03.350
Yet other people have managed to do that

856
00:32:03.380 --> 00:32:04.730
and not plagiarize. so...

857
00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:06.032
- Objection.
- PAGE: Sustained.

858
00:32:06.062 --> 00:32:08.028
Think I made my point. Your Honor.

859
00:32:08.058 --> 00:32:09.469
- Your witness.
- LUCCA: <i>Rowby.</i>

860
00:32:09.470 --> 00:32:12.368
can you show us how you composed
"Good Morning Magic Sunshine"?

861
00:32:12.398 --> 00:32:15.111
- Objection. Your Honor.
- No. I'd like to see this.

862
00:32:15.141 --> 00:32:18.381
- ROWBY: Uh. so this is SuperScribe.
- (Banging piano keys)

863
00:32:18.411 --> 00:32:21.464
I play notes on the keyboard.
and then they just populate

864
00:32:21.494 --> 00:32:24.694
into sheet music in real time.

865
00:32:25.838 --> 00:32:27.741
Uh. could you please. uh. play a little

866
00:32:27.771 --> 00:32:29.090
of "Good Morning Magic Sunshine"?

867
00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:30.277
Sure.

868
00:32:30.307 --> 00:32:32.379
(Playing piano)

869
00:32:33.323 --> 00:32:35.180
Acoustics are actually pretty good in here.

870
00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:36.822
You guys should rent it out for gigs.

871
00:32:36.852 --> 00:32:39.379
ALICIA: Thank you. Now can you
play "Moony Moonikins"?

872
00:32:39.580 --> 00:32:40.627
Yeah.

873
00:32:40.657 --> 00:32:42.810
(Playing piano)

874
00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:44.363
It's catchy. right?

875
00:32:46.185 --> 00:32:49.209
- Does no one have kids?
- Guilty. Adopted daughter from China.

876
00:32:49.239 --> 00:32:52.158
Could you please superimpose
the two songs you just played?

877
00:32:52.188 --> 00:32:54.379
If they're similar. they should overlap.

878
00:32:54.667 --> 00:32:56.023
As you can see. Your Honor.

879
00:32:56.053 --> 00:32:57.487
these two songs are nothing alike.

880
00:32:57.517 --> 00:32:59.010
Objection. Your Honor. he just left out

881
00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:00.816
the performance elements... the kazoo.

882
00:33:00.846 --> 00:33:03.518
the squeaky toy. the xylophone.
the shakers. the clapping...

883
00:33:03.548 --> 00:33:05.637
Because none of that is
legally copyrightable.

884
00:33:05.667 --> 00:33:07.590
With music. what you can copyright

885
00:33:07.620 --> 00:33:10.326
is the actual sound
recording or the composition.

886
00:33:10.356 --> 00:33:11.619
ALICIA: Any similarities here

887
00:33:11.620 --> 00:33:13.796
are the kind that are
not legally protected.

888
00:33:14.816 --> 00:33:17.166
What do you say to that. Ms. Stevens?

889
00:33:19.090 --> 00:33:21.000
Take this four-note run

890
00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:23.186
from "Magic Sunshine."

891
00:33:23.216 --> 00:33:24.453
(Plays notes)

892
00:33:24.483 --> 00:33:26.203
And this four-note run

893
00:33:26.233 --> 00:33:28.069
from "Moony."

894
00:33:28.070 --> 00:33:29.819
(Plays notes)

895
00:33:30.405 --> 00:33:31.439
Now look.

896
00:33:32.268 --> 00:33:33.529
They're virtually identical.

897
00:33:33.559 --> 00:33:35.024
ANDREA: So you see major similarities.

898
00:33:35.054 --> 00:33:37.527
Micro-segments are exactly the same.

899
00:33:37.557 --> 00:33:39.611
- Thank you.
- ALICIA: If you looked at micro-segments

900
00:33:39.641 --> 00:33:41.475
in a lot of children's songs.

901
00:33:41.505 --> 00:33:43.639
wouldn't there be many major similarities?

902
00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:44.580
- No.
- For example.

903
00:33:44.610 --> 00:33:47.059
isn't the theme from
<i>SpongeBob Squarepants</i>

904
00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:49.059
similar to the sea chantey
"Blow the Man Down"?

905
00:33:49.060 --> 00:33:50.328
I-I'm not familiar

906
00:33:50.358 --> 00:33:51.565
with the theme song you're talking about.

907
00:33:51.595 --> 00:33:53.195
What about the opening percussion riffs

908
00:33:53.225 --> 00:33:55.870
in the Supremes' version
of "You Can't Hurry Love"

909
00:33:55.900 --> 00:33:58.053
and Iggy Pop's "Lust for
Life"? Aren't they identical?

910
00:33:58.083 --> 00:34:00.480
You know. I... (sighs) I'm
not prepared to say that.

911
00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:01.716
Well. what about the chorus riff

912
00:34:01.746 --> 00:34:03.554
in Boston's "More Than a Feeling"

913
00:34:03.584 --> 00:34:05.224
and "Louie Louie" by the Kingsmen?

914
00:34:05.254 --> 00:34:06.957
Objection. Your Honor. This
is not <i>Name That Tune.</i>

915
00:34:06.987 --> 00:34:09.020
PAGE: This is getting a bit ridiculous.

916
00:34:09.050 --> 00:34:09.914
And that's our point.

917
00:34:09.944 --> 00:34:12.626
When you break a song down
into small enough components.

918
00:34:12.656 --> 00:34:14.531
you'll always find similarities.

919
00:34:14.561 --> 00:34:15.765
Don't break them down. then. Your Honor.

920
00:34:15.795 --> 00:34:16.880
Just listen to them together.

921
00:34:16.910 --> 00:34:19.069
Okay. okay. I've heard enough.

922
00:34:19.070 --> 00:34:21.333
I will take this under advisement.

923
00:34:21.363 --> 00:34:24.874
We'll reconvene for my
decision this afternoon.

924
00:34:25.525 --> 00:34:28.900
I found myself wrong about this firm.
so I gave it a second chance.

925
00:34:28.930 --> 00:34:30.830
She gave me a second chance.

926
00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:33.730
You say Bea Wilson is returning?

927
00:34:33.760 --> 00:34:34.850
Yes.

928
00:34:35.078 --> 00:34:36.344
Uh. she's thinking of returning.

929
00:34:36.374 --> 00:34:37.526
DAVID: She wasn't thrilled with having

930
00:34:37.556 --> 00:34:39.780
a law firm that works out
of an apartment building.

931
00:34:39.810 --> 00:34:41.136
(Groans) My God.

932
00:34:41.166 --> 00:34:42.840
There's this horrible woman there.

933
00:34:42.870 --> 00:34:43.490
Yes.

934
00:34:43.520 --> 00:34:44.790
Alicia can be quite trying.

935
00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:46.620
I don't think she means...

936
00:34:49.453 --> 00:34:51.103
Let me just close this.

937
00:34:54.181 --> 00:34:56.029
ANDREA: You know this
could go either way. right?

938
00:34:56.059 --> 00:34:56.729
Let's settle.

939
00:34:56.730 --> 00:34:57.581
What have you got?

940
00:34:57.611 --> 00:34:58.970
We can't break our contracts.

941
00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:00.228
It would set a bad precedent.

942
00:35:00.258 --> 00:35:02.669
but we could give Rowby a few points.

943
00:35:02.670 --> 00:35:04.811
A few? Seriously?

944
00:35:05.069 --> 00:35:05.789
Where's Rowby?

945
00:35:05.790 --> 00:35:07.590
Maybe he should hear this.

946
00:35:08.716 --> 00:35:10.169
- We're late.
- It's okay.

947
00:35:10.170 --> 00:35:12.367
- (Elevator bell dings)
- They can't start without us.

948
00:35:13.167 --> 00:35:14.869
Ms. Dunne? How are you?

949
00:35:15.165 --> 00:35:16.717
Good. Just going.

950
00:35:16.747 --> 00:35:17.709
I see that.

951
00:35:17.710 --> 00:35:20.560
You're dropping by the
office tomorrow. right?

952
00:35:21.194 --> 00:35:22.194
Right.

953
00:35:24.132 --> 00:35:25.579
You okay?

954
00:35:25.580 --> 00:35:27.580
That's one of our new clients.

955
00:35:27.660 --> 00:35:28.829
So?

956
00:35:29.144 --> 00:35:30.829
What's she doing here?

957
00:35:31.227 --> 00:35:32.669
They're stealing our clients.

958
00:35:33.128 --> 00:35:34.184
You should've seen her.

959
00:35:34.214 --> 00:35:35.329
She looked so guilty.

960
00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:38.080
Yes. Alicia Florrick
for Lila Dunne. please.

961
00:35:40.107 --> 00:35:41.107
I see.

962
00:35:41.137 --> 00:35:42.887
When will she be back in?

963
00:35:42.937 --> 00:35:45.037
- They screwed us.
- Thank you.

964
00:35:46.152 --> 00:35:47.669
Who else could they be going after?

965
00:35:48.152 --> 00:35:49.869
We haven't seen Bea Wilson in a while.

966
00:35:50.206 --> 00:35:51.946
She was supposed to call yesterday.

967
00:35:51.976 --> 00:35:53.980
- That would be bad.
- And Cary.

968
00:35:54.010 --> 00:35:55.589
Cary's been screwing us the whole time.

969
00:35:55.590 --> 00:35:57.169
(Phone rings)

970
00:35:57.579 --> 00:35:59.169
Alicia Florrick.

971
00:35:59.170 --> 00:36:01.009
Okay. We're on our way.

972
00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:03.474
Judge Page. she's made a decision.

973
00:36:03.504 --> 00:36:04.089
You go.

974
00:36:04.090 --> 00:36:06.640
I'm gonna stay here and call our clients.

975
00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:14.169
Hey. what's up?

976
00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:16.169
Hey. man.

977
00:36:16.170 --> 00:36:18.199
Andrea has another offer.

978
00:36:18.229 --> 00:36:19.279
Go to hell.

979
00:36:20.707 --> 00:36:21.759
Excuse me?

980
00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:23.089
BAILIFF: All rise.

981
00:36:23.090 --> 00:36:27.129
PAGE: ♪ Good morning. magic sunshine ♪

982
00:36:27.130 --> 00:36:28.378
♪ It's a brand-new day... ♪

983
00:36:28.408 --> 00:36:30.589
She likes it. She likes me.

984
00:36:30.590 --> 00:36:32.920
PAGE: Okay. this is what I know.

985
00:36:32.950 --> 00:36:36.169
"Good Morning. Magic
Sunshine" is a good song.

986
00:36:36.577 --> 00:36:38.040
And I don't even have kids.

987
00:36:38.070 --> 00:36:40.730
But when you start to chop it up.

988
00:36:40.760 --> 00:36:43.491
deconstruct it. you stop hearing it.

989
00:36:43.521 --> 00:36:46.989
And that's not how you're
supposed to listen to music.

990
00:36:46.990 --> 00:36:48.470
When I'm just experiencing

991
00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:50.583
these songs and not analyzing them.

992
00:36:50.613 --> 00:36:51.966
they sound the same.

993
00:36:51.996 --> 00:36:53.851
They simply have too much in common

994
00:36:53.881 --> 00:36:55.620
for this to be a coincidence.

995
00:36:55.650 --> 00:36:56.550
So...

996
00:36:56.580 --> 00:36:58.819
based on the evidence presented.

997
00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:01.508
I concluded. Mr. Canton.

998
00:37:01.538 --> 00:37:03.850
you stole that song.

999
00:37:04.040 --> 00:37:04.949
Summary judgment

1000
00:37:04.950 --> 00:37:06.870
- for the plaintiff.
- (Gavel bangs)

1001
00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:11.159
But. Bea. just give us a chance.

1002
00:37:11.350 --> 00:37:15.079
The advantage to working with
a small firm is dedication.

1003
00:37:15.080 --> 00:37:17.779
We don't split our duties.

1004
00:37:18.262 --> 00:37:19.349
Okay.

1005
00:37:19.350 --> 00:37:20.809
I'll await your call.

1006
00:37:21.455 --> 00:37:22.929
Can I help. Mom?

1007
00:37:22.930 --> 00:37:24.390
Make any calls?

1008
00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:26.279
No. I'm good.

1009
00:37:26.280 --> 00:37:27.130
No. seriously.

1010
00:37:27.160 --> 00:37:29.160
I'm done with all my homework.

1011
00:37:29.740 --> 00:37:31.779
Okay. then we should talk.

1012
00:37:31.780 --> 00:37:32.950
Uh-oh. (Chuckles)

1013
00:37:32.980 --> 00:37:34.730
Is it one of those talks?

1014
00:37:34.763 --> 00:37:35.763
Yes.

1015
00:37:35.913 --> 00:37:37.263
I'm afraid it is.

1016
00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:40.169
You know how much I love you. right?

1017
00:37:40.199 --> 00:37:42.089
And how much I appreciate

1018
00:37:42.090 --> 00:37:43.514
everything you're doing here.

1019
00:37:43.544 --> 00:37:44.693
for the firm. for me.

1020
00:37:44.723 --> 00:37:46.693
Mom. if it's about my
grades. I can bring them up.

1021
00:37:46.723 --> 00:37:48.077
- I promise you.
- You need to stop

1022
00:37:48.107 --> 00:37:50.273
working at Florrick/Quinn.

1023
00:37:52.564 --> 00:37:54.050
You're firing me?

1024
00:37:55.666 --> 00:37:56.929
Yes. I am.

1025
00:37:56.959 --> 00:37:59.118
But that's not fair. I've been doing
such a good job.

1026
00:37:59.148 --> 00:38:00.348
Yes. you have.

1027
00:38:00.735 --> 00:38:03.130
You have been doing an amazing job.

1028
00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:04.307
Too amazing. in fact.

1029
00:38:04.337 --> 00:38:06.890
So you're firing me for
doing too good a job?

1030
00:38:06.920 --> 00:38:08.859
- That has to be illegal.
- Grace.

1031
00:38:09.008 --> 00:38:12.300
you need to start focusing on
<i>your </i>future. not mine.

1032
00:38:12.330 --> 00:38:13.500
Mom. you need me.

1033
00:38:13.530 --> 00:38:15.285
Yes. as a daughter.

1034
00:38:15.315 --> 00:38:17.199
I so. so do.

1035
00:38:17.200 --> 00:38:18.869
But as a mother...

1036
00:38:19.112 --> 00:38:20.779
as your mother...

1037
00:38:21.459 --> 00:38:23.699
I need to be taking care of you.

1038
00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:25.000
not the reverse.

1039
00:38:26.467 --> 00:38:28.667
Do you understand what I'm saying?

1040
00:38:29.133 --> 00:38:30.529
I understand.

1041
00:38:30.530 --> 00:38:32.279
You want me to butt out of your life.

1042
00:38:33.054 --> 00:38:34.054
No.

1043
00:38:35.705 --> 00:38:36.805
My business.

1044
00:38:38.195 --> 00:38:40.699
Mom. you can't fire me and
hug me at the same time.

1045
00:38:40.700 --> 00:38:42.520
Oh. yes. I can.

1046
00:38:43.008 --> 00:38:44.215
(Chuckles)

1047
00:38:51.084 --> 00:38:52.184
Are you sad?

1048
00:38:52.869 --> 00:38:54.091
Well. kind of.

1049
00:38:54.121 --> 00:38:55.121
I don't like losing.

1050
00:38:55.151 --> 00:38:57.597
Yeah. me neither.

1051
00:39:02.675 --> 00:39:03.980
♪ 'Cause. Lucca ♪

1052
00:39:04.010 --> 00:39:05.969
♪ When you're near me ♪

1053
00:39:05.970 --> 00:39:09.130
♪ All is plain to see ♪

1054
00:39:11.109 --> 00:39:12.339
♪ That. Lucca ♪

1055
00:39:12.533 --> 00:39:14.418
♪ All that matters ♪

1056
00:39:14.448 --> 00:39:17.740
♪ Is you with me. ♪

1057
00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:26.629
(Song ends)

1058
00:39:27.028 --> 00:39:28.344
That's wonderful.

1059
00:39:28.588 --> 00:39:29.588
Thanks.

1060
00:39:29.883 --> 00:39:31.130
- Sell it.
- (Groans)

1061
00:39:31.130 --> 00:39:33.010
- To who?
- To anyone.

1062
00:39:34.339 --> 00:39:35.550
Yeah?

1063
00:39:37.519 --> 00:39:39.730
Change the name. though.

1064
00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:41.550
Whoa. where you going?

1065
00:39:42.496 --> 00:39:43.896
Back to real life.

1066
00:39:47.927 --> 00:39:49.127
What was this?

1067
00:39:50.245 --> 00:39:51.245
<i>(Knocking)</i>

1068
00:39:54.492 --> 00:39:56.011
So. you screwed us.

1069
00:39:56.041 --> 00:39:58.219
You mean did we try to poach
the clients you poached from us?

1070
00:39:58.220 --> 00:39:59.630
- Did you?
- Yes.

1071
00:40:00.108 --> 00:40:01.855
Great. Congratulations.

1072
00:40:01.885 --> 00:40:03.391
They said no.

1073
00:40:03.421 --> 00:40:04.919
We can't get ahold of our clients.

1074
00:40:04.920 --> 00:40:07.179
Yeah. because they're
saying no to you. too.

1075
00:40:07.839 --> 00:40:08.639
What does that mean?

1076
00:40:08.669 --> 00:40:09.927
They want you as lawyers.

1077
00:40:09.957 --> 00:40:11.549
but they want our infrastructure.

1078
00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:13.009
And if they can't have both.

1079
00:40:13.010 --> 00:40:14.230
they're gonna keep looking.

1080
00:40:14.260 --> 00:40:15.981
- How do you know that?
- They said it.

1081
00:40:16.011 --> 00:40:17.511
So why are you here?

1082
00:40:19.441 --> 00:40:21.291
Come back to Lockhart/Agos.

1083
00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:27.192
- No.
- Why not?

1084
00:40:27.222 --> 00:40:28.155
You fired me.

1085
00:40:28.185 --> 00:40:29.930
And I've never worked there.

1086
00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:32.289
We want you back.

1087
00:40:33.264 --> 00:40:35.414
And we want you to come with her.

1088
00:40:37.163 --> 00:40:38.213
Diane does?

1089
00:40:39.084 --> 00:40:41.384
Well. she understands the situation.

1090
00:40:44.432 --> 00:40:46.632
Thank you. but I'm not interested.

1091
00:40:47.290 --> 00:40:48.231
If you change your mind...

1092
00:40:48.261 --> 00:40:49.539
I won't. Thank you.

1093
00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:50.870
Bye.

1094
00:40:55.426 --> 00:40:57.314
Shall we at least discuss this?

1095
00:40:57.344 --> 00:40:59.432
- Okay.
- We're working out of your apartment.

1096
00:40:59.462 --> 00:41:01.512
We still have 70% DUIs.

1097
00:41:01.542 --> 00:41:03.450
We're barely making ends meet.

1098
00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:05.798
And we may have just
lost our top four clients.

1099
00:41:05.828 --> 00:41:07.578
And we don't have to answer to anyone.

1100
00:41:07.608 --> 00:41:09.558
Because no one else wants us.

1101
00:41:11.677 --> 00:41:13.439
Do you want to go and work for a big firm?

1102
00:41:13.469 --> 00:41:15.129
I don't know.

1103
00:41:15.399 --> 00:41:16.630
Maybe.

1104
00:41:19.207 --> 00:41:20.710
Well. I can't.

1105
00:41:21.682 --> 00:41:23.670
- So what do we do?
- (Knocking)

1106
00:41:24.187 --> 00:41:25.137
Oh. dear God.

1107
00:41:25.167 --> 00:41:26.167
(Sighs)

1108
00:41:29.451 --> 00:41:31.207
You have to forgive my dad.

1109
00:41:31.237 --> 00:41:32.079
Marissa.

1110
00:41:32.080 --> 00:41:35.169
I'm not here for him. I'm here for me.

1111
00:41:35.332 --> 00:41:37.580
- Hi.
- Hi. I'll leave you to it.

1112
00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:41.305
Did I interrupt something?

1113
00:41:41.335 --> 00:41:42.499
Yes.

1114
00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:44.079
(Sighs)

1115
00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:45.818
My dad cares about you. Alicia.

1116
00:41:45.994 --> 00:41:47.459
He only confessed to you what he did

1117
00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:48.869
because he was torn up about it.

1118
00:41:48.870 --> 00:41:50.287
He never had to confess.

1119
00:41:50.317 --> 00:41:51.669
You wouldn't have known.

1120
00:41:51.699 --> 00:41:53.299
No one would've known.

1121
00:41:53.626 --> 00:41:55.202
But he cares about you.

1122
00:41:55.232 --> 00:41:57.459
And my dad doesn't care about many people.

1123
00:41:57.460 --> 00:42:00.171
Yes. he did wrong. but let him apologize.

1124
00:42:00.201 --> 00:42:01.201
Let him...

1125
00:42:02.386 --> 00:42:03.386
What?

1126
00:42:04.162 --> 00:42:05.803
You're looking at me like
you want to tell me something.

1127
00:42:05.833 --> 00:42:07.383
Get lost? Go to hell?

1128
00:42:10.256 --> 00:42:11.369
No.

1129
00:42:11.674 --> 00:42:13.130
Then what?

1130
00:42:16.652 --> 00:42:18.670
I hurt.

1131
00:42:21.617 --> 00:42:22.920
I'm sorry.

1132
00:42:24.459 --> 00:42:26.039
It hurt me.

1133
00:42:26.359 --> 00:42:27.830
He knows that.

1134
00:42:30.975 --> 00:42:33.079
Then he can't expect anything more of me.

1135
00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:36.290
It would be unfair for him
to expect anything more.

1136
00:42:40.210 --> 00:42:43.002
Then let me say something.

1137
00:42:43.032 --> 00:42:45.395
Something very small.

1138
00:42:45.425 --> 00:42:47.825
Call him up and say. "You're forgiven.

1139
00:42:47.989 --> 00:42:49.668
"I need some time to not deal with you.

1140
00:42:49.698 --> 00:42:51.630
but you're forgiven."

1141
00:42:53.353 --> 00:42:54.353
I can't.

1142
00:42:55.339 --> 00:42:56.339
Please?

1143
00:42:59.922 --> 00:43:01.072
Marissa. I...

1144
00:43:07.221 --> 00:43:08.221
No.

1145
00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:13.420
(Sighs)

1146
00:43:20.336 --> 00:43:21.830
(Door opens)

1147
00:43:23.354 --> 00:43:24.504
(Door closes)

